Package com.googlecode.prmf.merapi.util.iterators

More iterator classes than you ever wanted to wrap your mind around.

          Description

Interface Summary
ReversibleIterator<T> Interface for an iterator whose traversal order can be reversed.
UniversalIterator<T> Interface combining Java's iterator, Iterable, and Enumeration with the Gang of Four iterator.
 

Class Summary
AbstractReversibleIterator<T> Subclass of AbstractUniversalIterator with a more specific return type for the iterator() method.
AbstractUniversalIterator<T> Skeleton implementation of a UniversalIterator.
ArrayIterator<T> An iterator over an array.
CharacterIterator An iterator over the characters of a CharSequence.
ContinuousIterator<T> An iterator that continuously loops over the elements of a traversal.
FileHierarchyIterator An iterator over a file hierarchy.
FilteredIterator<T> Applies a filter to a traversal.
GOFIteratorAdapter<T> Adapts a Gang of Four iterator to a UniversalIterator by wrapping it.
IteratorAdapter<T> Abstract adapter for iterators and other objects that are conceptually iterable.
JEnumerationAdapter<T> Adapter for an Enumeration.
JIteratorAdapter<T> Adapter for a Java iterator.
JListIterator<T> An iterator over a Java list.
JoiningIterator<T> An iterator that joins the traversals of a group of iterators into one.
LineIterator Abstract definition of an iterator that gets lines from an input source.
ListIterator<T> Abstract, template method-based iterator over a list or list-like structure.
MappingIterator<T,U> Applies a mapping function to a traversal.
MatchResultIterator An iterator over the captured groups of a MatchResult.
NodeHierarchyIterator An iterator over a Document Object Model node hierarchy.

ScannerIterator A line iterator that reads from a Scanner.
StreamIterator A line iterator that can read from an InputStream and related objects.
TreeIterator<T> Abstract, template method-based iterator over a tree or tree-like structure.
 

Package com.googlecode.prmf.merapi.util.iterators Description

More iterator classes than you ever wanted to wrap your mind around. Rather than using classes in this package directly, it's recommended that you use the methods of the Iterators class.
